Cyclistic Bikehire

Based in Chicago, Cyclstic looks to grow the company’s revenue by attracting its casual users to become members, paying an annual subscription for access to the service.

Business Task

*What marketing activities should be undertaken to convert casual riders to members on an annual subscription.

Data Files

The data files provided included 40 different files covering the last 8 years of cycle hires. From these it was necessary to only look at the last 12 months of data (Period Sept 2021 - Aug 2022) to review patterns in te data revealing the differences in behaviours of casual riders vs members.

Converting character attributes to factors

Upon inspecting the loaded dataset, it is clear that some character attributes have a limited set of values; they may be candidates to be converted to a factor datatype, allowing more efficient manipulation: 1. rideable_type 2. member_casual

The following commands reveal the unique values used in these attributes.

INSERT CODE CHUNK HERE TO SHOW UNIQUE VALUES OF MEMBER_CASUAL AND RIDEABLE_TYPE

Parsing datetime data

Fields containing datetime data are also parsed to POSIXct datatypes to facilitate appropriate calculations of duration and identifying patterns of when casual riders are most active users of the service across the day, week and calendar year. The timezone “America/Chicago” has been selected based on the business context.

#clean datatypes - factors for rideable_type and member_casual
#                - POSIXct (datetime) for started_at and ended_at
hires <- hires %>% 
  mutate(rideable_type = as.factor(rideable_type),
         member_casual=as.factor(member_casual),
         hire_date= as.POSIXct(started_at, format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S", tz = "America/Chicago"),
         return_date= as.POSIXct(ended_at, format = "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S", tz = "America/Chicago"),
         start_station_name = as.factor(start_station_name)
         )

Additional attributes added

Additional attributes were added to allow analysis and aggregation of the hires based on: 1. Duration of the hire (measured in minutes) 2. The month of the hire 3. The day of the week of the hire

#calculate hire duration in minutes
hires$mins_hired = difftime(hires$return_date, hires$hire_date, units="mins")

#separate out by month to allow grouping by month
hires$hired_year_month = format(hires$hire_date, "%Y-%m")

#add in day of the week hired
hires$weekday = ordered(weekdays(hires$hire_date), levels=c("Sunday", "Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday"))

#add in the hour when hire started
hires$start_hour = as.integer(format(hires$hire_date, "%H"))

Differences between member and casual riders

A key line of enquiry was to identify the differences between the members and the casual riders.

The following charts identify: 1. Casual riders are more likely to hire an electric bike compared to a classic bike 2. Casual riders also make use of the docked bike

#get mean ride duration for members vs casual riders by month
hires %>% group_by(member_casual) %>% count(rideable_type) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=member_casual, y=n)) +
  
  geom_bar(aes(fill=rideable_type), position="dodge", stat="identity", width=0.8, alpha=0.7, colour="black") + 
  ylab("Total Hires") + 
  xlab("Rider Type") + 
  labs(title="Total Hires by Rideable Type (Casual Riders vs Members), Sept '21 - Aug '22") +
  scale_fill_viridis(discrete = TRUE, name = "Rideable Type", labels = c("Classic Bike", "Docked Bike", "Electric Bike")) +
  scale_y_continuous()

The same data can be viewed as a pair of pie charts for comparison. This shows the creased preference for electric bikes with the Casual Riders compared to the Members.

casual_rideable_types <- hires %>% filter(member_casual=="casual") %>% count(rideable_type)
member_rideable_types <- hires %>% filter(member_casual=="member") %>% count(rideable_type)

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
pie(casual_rideable_types$n, labels=c("Classic Bike", "Docked Bike", "Electric Bike"), col=(viridis(3, option = "D")), main="Casual Riders")
pie(member_rideable_types$n, labels=c("Classic Bike", "Electric Bike"), col=(viridis(2, option = "D")), main="Members")

  1. Casual riders make greater use of the Cyclstic service on Saturday and Sunday compared to the week, indicating this is more likely a recreational activity for casual riders, rather than a mode of commute.
  2. Members tend to use the Cyclstic service more during the week and less on the weekend, indicating this is more likely a mode of commute for many members
hires %>% 
  group_by(member_casual) %>%

avg_duration_plot <- hires %>% group_by(member_casual, rideable_type) %>%

Headlines & Recommendations

Focus on the following three characteristics of Casual Riders’ behaviours when marketing to them, as they are dinstinct to existing Members’ characteristics and behaviours. - Casual riders tend to hire electric bikes and the ‘docked bike’ category more often compared to existing members. - Casual riders use the service on the weekend more than during the week, with highest activity between 10am and 6pm - Casual riders’ most popular docking stations tend to be in/adjacent to recreational spaces; Members’ most popular stations tend to be situated in built up areas
